\section{Discussion}
\begin{frame}{Discussion and conclusions (1)}

The principal conclusions of this analysis are:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item There has been a \textbf{variation in snow cover} from 2016 to 2022. In particular, the percentage of snow varied \textbf{from 26,15\%} in 2016 to \textbf{15,60\%} in 2022. This could probably but not certainly be due to rising temperatures in recent years.\\
    \item This variation can be clearly seen in all the images plotted: the RGB ones and the NDSI index ones.\\
    \item The function \textbf{im.classify()} to create the 2 clusters seems to shown \textbf{good results} in indicating the areas where the snow is present or not.

    
        \end{enumerate}
    \end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Discussion and conclusions (2)}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item From the NDVI index computation it can be noted that the areas cover with values around 0 (that indicate also snow) are \textbf{less extended at t2} compared to t1: this is another confirmation of the decrease in snow cover. 
    \item There are also more values of NDVI close to 1 (dark green area) at t1, and this indicates that in this period \textbf{plants} in the studied area \textbf{were healthier} in comparison with t2.

        \end{enumerate}
    \end{frame}

